Assert: verb. &quot;To state or declare positively and often forcefully or
aggressively.&quot;  (m-w.com)

When you call assert() or one of its siblings, you are saying, &quot;I know this
fact to be true, so please abort this operation right away if somehow it
isn&#39;t!&quot;

Asserts can be very useful in production code, but there are a number of
considerations to... consider... which would be off-topic right now.  In the
context of JUnit, though, they&#39;re the meat and potatoes of nearly any test
case you write.  They&#39;re how JUnit knows whether your test passed or
failed--if any assert fails, the test fails, and if no assert fails (and no
exception is thrown), the test passes.

By the way, all the different varieties of assert() are fundamentally
equivalent, but each is tailored to provide a more descriptive failure
message for its particular usage.  For example, 

    assertEquals(&quot;Value of b&quot;, a, b);

is functionally identical to

    assert(a.equals(b));

But where the former gives an error message like:

    Value of b expected: &lt;1&gt; but was:&lt;2&gt;

The latter gives just:

    junit.framework.AssertionFailedError

Quite a difference!

Kevin


